<p><b>David Kahn</b> (b. February 7, 1930<sup id="cite_ref-contem_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-contem-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup>) is a US historian, journalist and writer. He has written extensively on the history of <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cryptography" title="Cryptography">cryptography</a> and <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Military_intelligence" title="Military intelligence">military intelligence</a>.</p>
<p>Kahn's first published book, <i><a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Codebreakers_-_The_Story_of_Secret_Writing" title="The Codebreakers - The Story of Secret Writing" class="mw-redirect">The Codebreakers - The Story of Secret Writing</a></i> (1967), was widely considered to be a definitive account of the <a href="http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/History_of_cryptography" title="History of cryptography">history of cryptography</a> up to the mid-1960s.</p>
<p></p>
<div id="toc" class="toc">
